                    <div class="collapse-title font-semibold">the difference between var, let, and const?</div>
                    <div class="collapse-content text-sm"><strong>var</strong> is function-scoped, allows re-declaration
                        and re-assignment, and is hoisted with undefined. <br>
                        <strong> let </strong>is block-scoped, does not allow re-declaration but allows re-assignment.
                        <br>
                        <strong>const</strong> is block-scoped, does not allow re-declaration or re-assignment, and its
                        value remains constant.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="collapse collapse-plus bg-gray-200 border border-base-300 my-2">
                    <input type="radio" name="my-accordion-3" />
                    <div class="collapse-title font-semibold">the difference between map(), forEach(), and filter()?
                    </div>
                    <div class="collapse-content text-sm">

                        <strong>map()</strong> returns a new array with modified elements without changing the original
                        array. <br>
                        <strong>forEach()</strong> executes a function for each element but does not return a new
                        array. <br>
                        <strong>filter()</strong> returns a new array with elements that meet a specific condition. <br>

                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="collapse collapse-plus bg-gray-200 border border-base-300 my-2">
                    <input type="radio" name="my-accordion-3" />
                    <div class="collapse-title font-semibold">explain arrow functions and how they are different from regular functions?</div>
                    <div class="collapse-content text-sm"><strong>Arrow functions</strong> use => for a shorter syntax, inherit this from the surrounding scope, support implicit <br> return, cannot be used as constructors, and lack the arguments object, unlike regular functions.</div>
                </div>
                <div class="collapse collapse-plus bg-gray-200 border border-base-300 my-2">
                    <input type="radio" name="my-accordion-3" />
                    <div class="collapse-title font-semibold"> how JavaScript Promises work?</div>
                    <div class="collapse-content text-sm"><strong>JavaScript Promises</strong> handle asynchronous operations. A Promise has three states: pending, resolved <br> (fulfilled), or rejected. It executes asynchronously and uses .then() for success and .catch() for errors.</div>
                </div>
                <div class="collapse collapse-plus bg-gray-200 border border-base-300 my-2">
                    <input type="radio" name="my-accordion-3" />
                    <div class="collapse-title font-semibold">how closures work in JavaScript?</div>
                    <div class="collapse-content text-sm"><strong>Closures</strong> in JavaScript occur when a function retains access to its lexical scope, even after the outer <br> function has finished executing. This allows the inner function to access variables from the outer <br> function, even after it's returned.</div>
                </div>
            </div>
